summary: How do you people remember when you've started watching a youtuber?
body:
How do you people remember when you’ve started watching a youtuber?

Like I see everywhere how people say: “I’ve started watching *youtuber’s name* in 2011 on the 21st of September at 3 a.m. and the video was *title of the video*”. Hoooow?

I’ve spend a week trying to remember when I’ve started watching Pewds and I only can say it smth around 5 years, only cause I remember taking about him at school… maybe… probably… not sure

What kind of magic are you using?

summary: Okay, so, a video by this YouTuber popped into my recommended. I saw this video in my recommended, whole title being “The Rise...
body:
Okay, so, a video by this YouTuber popped into my recommended.

I saw this video in my recommended,

whole title being “The Rise of Romanticising Mental Illnesses & Why It Must Be Stopped”.

After watching this whole video, I saw he used trigger warnings correctly, called out people making money off of mental illness, I thought “Okay, seems like a good dude! I’ll browse his channel.” I decided to look at older videos first, so I sorted his videos from oldest to newest and…

these videos were there.

If you want to know how close these were to each other without me singling them out:

My first thought after seeing all of these is “Wow! This guy is a total hypocrite!”

How are you going to complain people are romanticizing mental illness and then give yourself a free pass to use ableist terms? I have psychosis, but I don’t use the term “psycho.” I have dissociative identity disorder and never use the term “alter ego.” Why is it not okay for other people to wear a shirt that says “my anxieties have anxieties”, but then you can do this?

Notice how these are all within a year? He made four videos with ableist titles, but then one saying how it’s wrong to romanticize it. How does that make sense?

I’m speechless.
